<p>Solar installation costs in Connecticut have decreased significantly over the past decade while system quality and efficiency have improved. Current pricing averages \$3.05-3.20 per watt installed for residential systems, with economies of scale favoring larger installations. Equipment costs include high-efficiency monocrystalline panels, string inverters or power optimizers, mounting hardware, electrical components, and monitoring systems. Installation costs cover permits, inspections, electrical work, roof mounting, and system commissioning.</p>

<p>The federal 30% Investment Tax Credit significantly improves solar economics, reducing the effective cost by nearly one-third. For a typical 7kW system costing \$21,700 before incentives, the tax credit provides \$6,510 in savings, bringing the net investment to \$15,190. Based on Connecticut's high electricity rates of 21.6 cents per kWh, this system would generate annual savings of \$1,550-1,800, creating a simple payback period of 8.5-9.8 years. Over the system's 25-year warranty period, total savings typically exceed \$35,000-40,000.</p>

<h2>HVAC Systems in Connecticut</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Connecticut's humid continental climate presents unique challenges for HVAC systems, requiring equipment capable of handling temperature extremes ranging from sub-zero winter conditions to summer highs approaching 90¬∞F with significant humidity. The state experiences approximately 6,200 heating degree days annually, indicating substantial heating requirements during the October through April heating season. Cooling demands, while less intense, still require 650-800 cooling degree days annually, particularly during July and August when humidity levels frequently exceed 70%.</p>

<p>Winter heating represents the largest energy expense for most Connecticut homeowners, with natural gas, heating oil, and electricity being the primary fuel sources. The state's older housing stock, much of it built before modern energy codes, often suffers from inadequate insulation and air sealing, placing additional demands on HVAC systems. Modern high-efficiency heat pumps, including cold-climate models capable of operating effectively at temperatures down to -15¬∞F, are increasingly popular as they can provide both heating and cooling while reducing overall energy consumption.</p>

<p>Indoor air quality considerations are particularly important in Connecticut due to the state's long heating season requiring homes to remain sealed for extended periods. Proper ventilation, humidity control, and filtration become critical components of HVAC system design. Whole-house dehumidification during summer months and humidification during winter help maintain comfort while preventing moisture-related issues such as mold growth or excessive drying that can damage wood floors and furniture.</p>

