<p>HVAC system costs in Connecticut vary significantly based on system type, home size, existing infrastructure, and installation complexity. High-efficiency natural gas furnaces with 95% Annual Fuel Utilization Efficiency (AFUE) ratings represent substantial improvements over older 80% efficiency units, particularly given Connecticut's long heating season. The premium for high-efficiency equipment is typically recovered through energy savings within 8-12 years, with continued savings throughout the equipment's 15-20 year lifespan.</p>

<p>Cold-climate heat pumps have gained popularity in Connecticut as technology improvements have made them viable alternatives to traditional heating systems even in harsh winter conditions. These systems provide both heating and cooling, eliminating the need for separate furnace and air conditioning equipment. Modern cold-climate heat pumps maintain high efficiency ratings down to -15¬∞F and can provide supplemental heating to temperatures as low as -25¬∞F, covering virtually all of Connecticut's weather conditions while providing annual energy savings of \$800-1,200 compared to older heating systems.</p>

<p>Ductless mini-split systems offer excellent efficiency and zoning capabilities, particularly valuable in Connecticut homes where room-by-room temperature control can significantly reduce energy consumption. These systems work exceptionally well for additions, finished basements, or homes without existing ductwork. Installation costs are generally lower than ducted systems, and the ability to condition only occupied spaces can provide substantial energy savings in larger homes.</p>

<h2>Connecticut Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Connecticut offers robust financial incentives for both solar panel installations and energy-efficient HVAC systems, significantly improving the economics of these investments. The federal 30% Investment Tax Credit applies to solar installations through 2032, providing dollar-for-dollar tax credit reductions equal to 30% of the total system cost, including equipment, installation, permits, and sales tax. For a typical \$20,000 solar installation, this credit provides \$6,000 in tax savings, substantially reducing the net investment and accelerating payback periods.</p>

<p>The state's SMART-E Loan Program, administered by the Connecticut Green Bank, provides low-interest financing for energy efficiency improvements including high-efficiency HVAC systems, insulation, windows, and other qualifying upgrades. The program offers loans up to \$50,000 for residential projects with terms up to 12 years and interest rates starting at 4.99%. On-bill financing options allow customers to repay loans through their utility bills, with the goal of ensuring monthly loan payments are less than monthly energy savings generated by the improvements.</p>

<p>Eversource Energy provides additional rebates and incentives for customers upgrading to high-efficiency equipment. The Home Energy Solutions program offers comprehensive energy assessments and rebates up to \$10,000 for qualifying improvements. Heat pump installations can qualify for rebates ranging from \$500-2,000 depending on system efficiency and type. The utility also offers seasonal promotions and enhanced rebates for customers participating in demand response programs that help reduce peak electricity usage during high-demand periods.</p>

<p>Connecticut's Property Assessed Clean Energy (PACE) financing program allows property owners to finance renewable energy and efficiency improvements through voluntary assessments on their property tax bills. PACE financing can cover up to 100% of project costs with repayment terms up to 20 years, and the assessment transfers to new owners if the property is sold. This program is particularly valuable for larger projects combining solar installations with comprehensive HVAC upgrades, allowing homeowners to bundle improvements while maintaining positive cash flow from day one.</p>

